ency, you may not be able to do this before you leave work but you should let your employer know as soon as possible. </p>\n\n<p>You don&rsquo;t have to do this in writing or give written proof. </p>\n\n<h2>How much time can you take off?</h2>\n<p>You&rsquo;re allowed a reasonable time - there isn&rsquo;t a set amount of time but usually 1 or 2 days is enough.</p>\n\n<p>For example if your child falls ill you could take time off to go to the doctor and make care arrangements but you&rsquo;d have to take <a href=\"/holiday-entitlement-rights\" title=\"Holiday entitlement: your rights\">annual</a> or <a href=\"/parental-leave\" title=\"Parental leave\">parental leave</a> if you wanted to look after your child for longer. </p>\n\n<h2>Limits on time off</h2>\n<p>There are no limits on how many times you can take time off for dependants but your employer should talk to you if they think it&rsquo;s having an effect on your work. </p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/time-off-for-dependants/problems-when-you-take-time-off","slug":"problems-when-you-take-time-off","order":4,"title":"Problems when you take time off","body":"<p>Your employer musn&rsquo;t:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>treat you unfairly for taking time off (for example refusing you training or promotion)</li>\n  <li>dismiss you or choose you for redundancy because you asked for time off for a dependant</li>\n  <li>refuse you reasonable time off </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you think you&rsquo;ve been unfairly treated for taking time off for dependants, get advice from your staff or trade union representative or ACAS. </p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>ACAS helpline</strong><br />\n08457 474 747</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>You may be able to take a case to an <a href=\"/employment-tribunals\" title=\"Employment tribunals\">Employment Tribunal</a>.</p>\n"}]},"updated_at":"2012-11-01T16:50:07+00:00","tags":[{"title":"Holidays, time off, sick leave, maternity and paternity leave","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/working%2Ftime-o